# GridLink — The Procurement Operating System for Fuel

## Product Context
GridLink is an AI-powered fuel procurement platform — think LinkedIn meets Procore for the fuel industry. It connects enterprise fuel buyers (food/ag, logistics, manufacturing, airports, hospitals, utilities, government) with verified fuel suppliers nationwide.

The core value prop: replace email + spreadsheet procurement with a centralized, audit-trail system of record.

## Design References
- **Procore** — enterprise dashboard polish, clean data density
- **FuelMe** — the onboarding form structure (we're modeling this directly)
- **Quest CDN** — bid/RFP layouts
- **Met Council** — contracting opportunities list design

## Visual Style
- **Primary color:** Deep navy `#0A2540` (trust, enterprise)
- **Accent:** Electric blue `#3B82F6` (CTAs, GridLink Verified badge)
- **Success/Verified:** Emerald `#10B981`
- **Background:** White / `#F9FAFB`
- **Typography:** Inter (already in Next.js default)
- **Feel:** Enterprise SaaS. Generous whitespace. Crisp borders. Subtle shadows. NOT a flashy startup landing page — investors should see "this looks like Procore."

## Code Conventions
- Next.js 14 App Router, TypeScript strict mode
- Server components by default, `"use client"` only when needed
- shadcn/ui for all UI primitives — no custom button components
- Tailwind utility classes, no CSS modules
- React Hook Form + Zod for ALL forms
- Supabase for auth, DB, storage
- File structure:
  - `/src/app` — routes
  - `/src/components` — shared components
  - `/src/components/ui` — shadcn primitives (don't modify)
  - `/src/lib` — utilities, supabase client, types
  - `/src/lib/schemas` — Zod schemas
  - `/src/lib/types.ts` — shared TS types

## Routing Structure
- `/` — Marketing landing page
- `/become-a-supplier` — Public interest form
- `/vendor-registration/[token]` — Vendor onboarding form (token-gated, no login)
- `/login` — Unified login (role-based redirect)
- `/signup` — Buyer signup only (vendors signup via approval flow)
- `/buyer/*` — Buyer dashboard routes
- `/vendor/*` — Vendor dashboard routes
- `/admin/*` — GridLink admin panel
- `/directory` — Public-facing GridLink Verified Directory (buyer auth required to view full profiles)

## User Roles (in order of access)
1. `buyer` — enterprise procurement user
2. `vendor` — verified fuel supplier
3. `admin` — GridLink team (reviews, approves, manages platform)

## Critical Workflows
1. **Vendor onboarding has TWO entry points**: GridLink invites OR vendor self-applies via "Become a Supplier"
2. **Vendor does NOT create credentials until AFTER admin approval** — they fill out the form via a one-time token link, get reviewed, and only then receive a "Create Account" email.
3. **GridLink Verified** is the core badge — granted only after admin review of company info, insurance, certifications, and compliance docs.
4. **The Verified Directory** is the most important screen. It must support multi-faceted filtering: state, products offered, capabilities, certifications, annual gallons, emergency response time.

## Don'ts
- Don't build AI/ML features yet — MVP is rules-based
- Don't build payments
- Don't build the actual bid-matching/award engine — just the RFP creation, response collection, and side-by-side comparison view
- Don't over-engineer. Demo-quality > production-quality for July 10.
